'''[[Homelessness]] in Spain''' is a significant social issue, affecting some 40,000 people<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.homelessworldcup.org/homelessness-statistics/|title=Global Homelessness Statistics - Homeless World Cup|publisher=}}</ref> (0.09% of [[Demographics of Spain|the population]].) Migrants are disproportionately represented among the homeless population.<ref>Meda, Jordi Bosch. "Homelessness among migrants in Spain." European Journal of Homelessness (2010): 139.</ref> Young people are also highly represented among the homeless, some studies estimating that 30% of Spain's homeless are aged 18-29.<ref>Quilgars, Deborah. "Youth homelessness." Homelessness Research in Europe. Brussels: FEANTSA (European Federation of National Associations Working with the Homeless) (2010): 187-210.</ref>

Mental illness among homeless is thought to occur less frequently than the US, this may be attributed to Spain's universal healthcare system.<ref>Philippot, Pierre, Catherine Lecocq, Fanny Sempoux, Hilde Nachtergael, and Benoit Galand. "Psychological research on homelessness in Western Europe: A review from 1970 to 2001." Journal of Social Issues 63, no. 3 (2007): 483-503.</ref> One study found high levels of substance-related disorders, but these rates were comparatively lower than US and UK samples.<ref>Vázquez, Carmelo, Manuel Muñoz, and Jesus Sanz. "Lifetime and 12‐month prevalence of DSM‐III‐R mental disorders among the homeless in Madrid: a European study using the CIDI." Acta Psychiatrica Scandinavica 95, no. 6 (1997): 523-530.</ref> Other researchers note that such comparative studies run the challenge of lack of prepared official definition of homelessness, as well as few well-controlled studies.<ref>Vázquez, Carmelo, and Manuel Muñoz. "Homelessness, Mental Health, and Stressful Life Events: The Madrid Experience." International Journal of Mental Health 30, no. 3 (2001): 6-25.</ref>

in 2015, a former minister and leader of the conservative Popular Party stated that homeless people sleeping in the streets are “scaring off” tourists from Madrid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/spain/11569171/Get-rid-of-the-homeless-people-in-Madrid-who-scare-tourists-former-Spanish-minister-says.html|title=Get rid of the homeless people in Madrid who scare tourists, former Spanish minister says|publisher=}}</ref>

