'''Joseph Silver Hyder''' (died 1932) was secretary to the Land Nationalisation Society in Britain.
[[Alfred Russel Wallace]] wrote an introduction to Hyder's work ''The Case for Land Nationalisation'' (1914, London: Simpkin, Marshall, Hamilton, Kent and co.),<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hyder|first1=Joseph|title=The Case for Land Nationalisation|date=1914|publisher=Simpkin, Marshall, Hamilton, Kent & co.|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924032455465#page/n5/mode/2up|accessdate=22 June 2016}}</ref> and Hyder was one of the small gathering who attended Wallace's funeral in 1913.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Slotten|first1=Ross A.|title=The Heretic in Darwin's Court: The Life of Alfred Russel Wallace|date=2012|isbn=9780231503563|page=490|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zeNOFryZZ5cC&lpg=PA490&dq=%22joseph%20hyder%22&pg=PA490#v=onepage&q=%22joseph%20hyder%22&f=false|accessdate=22 June 2016|chapter=A national treasure celebrated}}</ref>
Hyder stood as a [[Progressive Party (London)|Progressive Party]] candidate at [[Strand (UK Parliament constituency)|Strand]] in the [[London County Council election, 1904]].<ref>The Times, 8 March 1904</ref>
